D.C. State of Mind

On Thursday, I made an impromptu trip down to Washington, D.C., to tend to =
some business, see a few people, and catch the flavor of the capital amid t=
his administrative transition. Owing to some last-minute flight delays, I e=
nded up opting for the Acela=E2=80=94always the smarter choice, honestly=E2=
=80=94and subsequently descended through the metaphorical journey of this l=
arger presidential campaign.

The train started in New York, the former stomping grounds of the next pres=
ident, through Philadelphia, where Kamala Harris concluded her campaign, an=
d then Wilmington, its erstwhile base of operation, down to Union Station, =
a quick walk from the White House. Barreling past the fall foliage, I spent=
 much of the ride contemplating the impact that the forthcoming Trump admin=
istration will have on our industry.

Trump=E2=80=99s original
ascent, back in 2016, caught much of the media by surprise, and some of the=
 sector=E2=80=99s largest companies spent the subsequent four years engaged=
 in daily journalistic combat with the White House. This so-called #Resista=
nce era, which was defined by Trump=E2=80=99s many scandals (and dual impea=
chments) in addition to the Times and Post=E2=80=99s rocketing subscriber n=
umbers and CNN=E2=80=99s record revenues, was a boon for the media business=
 and democratic activism, alike.

Now, however, the era seems like a relic. The Trump phenomenon is no longer=
 novel or even a phenomenon=E2=80=94the guy has effectively placed himself =
at the nucleus of the Republican establishment. Meanwhile, the media indust=
ry has balkanized considerably in the intervening years. A decade ago, Trum=
p=E2=80=99s rise represented a broad shock that was processed through what =
remained of the monoculture. These days, media companies are more efficient=
 and specialized and personality-driven and, well, smaller.

And many of them, like the Post and CNN, have been unequivocally humbled. P=
aramount Global, the parentco of CBS, is in the process of a sale to the El=
lison family and RedBird Capital. Last week, Comcast president Mike Cavanag=
h intimated that he=E2=80=99d be open to spinning off his company=E2=80=99s=
 cable networks, including MSNBC and CNBC. Six years after buying Time for =
$190 million, Marc Benioff is unloading it at a loss.

Naturally, my partners were examining the same question with far more exper=
tise and aplomb. Dylan Byers takes on this consequential question in his ch=
aracteristically brilliant piece The #Resistance Is Futile ( https://puck.n=
ews/the-trump-resistance-is-futile/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIB=
ERS+%2811%2F9%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io ). Trump, after all, came al=
ong when the media industry was
beginning to lose its nerve. Now, he=E2=80=99s reappeared at an even more v=
exing, more critical moment=E2=80=94all of which leads us to believe that t=
he future will not replicate the past.

Matt Belloni, meanwhile, offers some typically peerless analysis on how the=
 entertainment industry is bracing for the Trump revival. In Why Hollywood =
Executives Are So Giddy About Trump 2.0 ( https://puck.news/why-are-hollywo=
od-executives-so-giddy-about-trump/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIB=
ERS+%2811%2F9%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io ), Matt recognizes that the =
transactional president may become the surprising accelerant for a legacy b=
usiness in need of consolidation. Meanwhile, the great John Ourand captures=
 the methodical way in which the folks in Bristol prepared for this moment.=
 Republicans Buy ESPN Subscriptions, Too ( https://puck.news/republicans-bu=
y-espn-subscriptions-too/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%=
2F9%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io ) is a thought-provoking work sure to =
make the rounds in executive suites this week.

But if you=E2=80=99re looking to curl up by the fire this weekend with a de=
cidedly apolitical piece, I=E2=80=99d turn your attention to Lauren Sherman=
=E2=80=99s most recent masterstroke, Vuitton=E2=80=99s Retro Trick & Gucci=
=E2=80=99s New Story ( https://puck.news/louis-vuittons-murakami-revival-di=
or-difficulties-more/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F9%=
2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io ), which examines the challenges plaguing =
two of the world=E2=80=99s largest fashion
brands. It=E2=80=99s delicious and insider-y and full of insights on how br=
ands are marketing themselves in the modern global economy, whether or not =
Trump is ultimately able to impose his preferred tariff policies. Indeed, i=
t is one of the great stories of our time, amid these changing times, and p=
recisely what you should always expect from Puck.

Have a great weekend,
Jon

