          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">On Thursday, I made=
 an impromptu trip down to Washington, D.C., to tend to some business, see =
a few people, and catch the flavor of the capital amid this administrative =
transition. Owing to some last-minute flight delays, I ended up opting for =
the Acela=E2=80=94always the smarter choice, honestly=E2=80=94and subsequen=
tly descended through the metaphorical journey of this larger presidential =
campaign. <br/><br/>The train started in New York, the former stomping grou=
nds of the next president, through Philadelphia, where <b>Kamala Harris </b=
>concluded her campaign, and then Wilmington, its erstwhile base of operati=
on, down to Union Station, a quick walk from the White House. Barreling pas=
t the fall foliage, I spent much of the ride contemplating the impact that =
the forthcoming <b>Trump </b>administration will have on our industry. <br/=
><br/>Trump=E2=80=99s original
ascent, back in 2016, caught much of the media by surprise, and some of the=
 sector=E2=80=99s largest companies spent the subsequent four years engaged=
 in daily journalistic combat with the White House. This so-called #Resista=
nce era, which was defined by Trump=E2=80=99s many scandals (and dual impea=
chments) in addition to the <i>Times </i>and <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s rocketin=
g subscriber numbers and CNN=E2=80=99s record revenues, was a boon for the =
media business and democratic activism, alike. <br/><br/>Now, however, the =
era seems like a relic. The Trump phenomenon is no longer novel or even a p=
henomenon=E2=80=94the guy has effectively placed himself at the nucleus of =
the Republican establishment. Meanwhile, the media industry has balkanized =
considerably in the intervening years. A decade ago, Trump=E2=80=99s rise r=
epresented a broad shock that was processed through what remained of the mo=
noculture. These days, media companies are more efficient and specialized a=
nd personality-driven and, well, <i>smaller</i>.
<br/><br/>And many of them, like the <i>Post </i>and CNN, have been unequiv=
ocally humbled. Paramount Global, the parentco of CBS, is in the process of=
 a sale to the <b>Ellison </b>family and RedBird Capital. Last week, Comcas=
t president  <b>Mike Cavanagh </b>intimated that he=E2=80=99d be open to sp=
inning off his company=E2=80=99s cable networks, including MSNBC and CNBC. =
Six years after buying <i>Time </i>for $190 million, <b>Marc Benioff</b> is=
 unloading it at a loss. <br/><br/>Naturally, my partners were examining th=
e same question with far more expertise and aplomb. <b>Dylan Byers </b>take=
s on this consequential question in his characteristically brilliant piece =
<i><u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQU=
t2UktxclJLZ0dURVN2a1JLNHRtWmo2MkVFRkY1bz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld=
3MvdGhlLXRydW1wLXJlc2lzdGFuY2UtaXMtZnV0aWxlLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249VGhlK0JhY2tz=
dG9yeSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODExJTJGOSUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN=
0b21lci5pbyIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MTk2Nj=
kzMX0/649381ad090e730b4af81cc6d478ce02f964badfebde1bd9dbb9dbb321125c3e" sty=
le=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">Th=
e #Resistance Is Futile</a></u></i>. Trump, after all, came along when the =
media industry was
beginning to lose its nerve. Now, he=E2=80=99s reappeared at an even more v=
exing, more critical moment=E2=80=94all of which leads us to believe that t=
he future will not replicate the past.<br/><br/><b>Matt Belloni</b>, meanwh=
